'''Tiruchirappalli''' ({{Lang-ta|<U+0BA4><U+0BBF><U+0BEB><U+0B9A><U+0BCD><U+0B9A><U+0BBF><U+0BB0><U+0BBE><U+0BAA><U+0BCD><U+0BAA><U+0BB3><U+0BCD><U+0BB3><U+0BBF>}} (''tiruccir<U+0101>ppa<U+1E37><U+1E37>i'') {{audio|Tiruchirapalli.ogg|pronunciation}}) (spelt as '''Trichinopoly''' in the records of [[British India]]), also called '''Tiruchi''' or '''Trichy''' ({{Lang-ta|<U+0BA4><U+0BBF><U+0BEB><U+0B9A><U+0BCD><U+0B9A><U+0BBF>}}),  is a [[city]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]] and the administrative headquarters of [[Tiruchirapalli District]]. It is the fourth largest [[municipal corporation]] in Tamil Nadu and also the fourth largest [[urban agglomeration]] in the state. Situated at a distance of {{Convert|325|km}} south of [[Chennai]] and {{Convert|402|km}} north of [[Kanyakumari]] on the [[National Highway (India)|National Highway]] NH 45, it is located almost at the geographic centre of the state. 

Tiruchirappalli is believed to have been named after the three-headed demon [[Trishira]] of Hindu mythology who is believed to have indulged in penance and obtained favours at this place. The city is believed to be of significant antiquity and has been ruled by the [[Early Cholas]], Early Pandyas, [[Pallavas]], [[Medieval Cholas]], [[Later Cholas]], Later Pandyas, [[Delhi Sultanate]], [[Ma'bar Sultanate]], [[Vijayanagar Empire]], [[Nayak Dynasty]], the [[Nawab of the Carnatic|Carnatic state]] and the [[United Kingdom|British]] at different times. The archaeologically important town of [[Uraiyur]] which served as the capital of the Early Cholas is a suburb of Tiruchirappalli. Tiruchirappalli has a number of historical monuments, the ''[[Rockfort]]'', [[Srirangam Ranganathaswamy temple|Ranganathaswamy temple at Srirangam]] and the [[Jambukeswarar Temple, Thiruvanaikaval|Jambukeswarar temple at Thiruvanaikaval]] being the most prominent among them.

Tiruchirappalli is an important industrial and educational hub of central Tamil Nadu. The factories of [[Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited]] (BHEL), [[Heavy Alloy Penetrator Project]] and [[Golden Rock Locomotive Workshops|Golden Rock Railway Workshops]] are located in Tiruchirappalli. The [[National Institutes of Technology]] (NIT), [[Bharathidasan University]], [[Bharathidasan Institute of Management]] and [[Anna University of Technology, Tiruchirappalli|Anna University of Technology]] have their campuses in the city.

==Etymology==
The name Tiruchirappalli is believed by some to have been derived from the Sanskrit "Trishirapuram" - 'Trishira' meaning "three-headed" and 'palli' or 'puram' meaning "City".<ref name="hemingwayp2">[[#Hemingway|Hemingway]], p 2</ref><ref name="frommersindiap350">{{cite book|title=Frommer's India|page=350|first1=Pippa|last1=de Bruyn|first2=Keith|last2=Bain|first3=David|last3=Allardice|id=ISBN 0-470-55610-2, ISBN 978-0-470-55610-8|publisher=Frommer's|year=2010}}</ref><ref name="hobsonjobson">{{cite book|title=Hobson-Jobson: A glossary of colloquial Anglo-Indian words and phrases|chapter=Trichinopoly|url=http://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.2:1:368.hobson|publisher=J. Murray|year=1903|first1=Sir Henry|last1=Yule|authorlink1=Sir Henry Yule|first2=Arthur Coke|last2=Burnell|authorlink2=Arthur Coke Burnell|page=938}}</ref> According to [[Hindu mythology]], the town got its name from the three-headed [[demon]] [[Trishira]] who meditated on the [[Hindu god]] [[Shiva]] near the present-day Tiruchirappalli and obtained favours at this place.<ref name="hemingwayp2" /><ref name="footprintp125">[[#Bradnock|Bradnock et al.]], p 125</ref> However, this derivation is not universally accepted.<ref name="hemingwayp2" />

Other derivations of Tiruchirappalli have been provided by the [[Telugu language|Telugu]] scholar [[C. P. Brown]] who suggested that Tiruchirappalli might be a derivative of the word 'Chiruta-palli' meaning "little town".<ref name="hemingwayp2" /><ref name="hobsonjobson" /> In an inscription of the sixteenth century, Tiruchirappalli is mentioned as ''Tiru-ssila-palli'' meaning "holy-rock-town" in Tamil and [[Henry Yule]] and [[Arthur Coke Burnell]] believed that the name Tiruchirappalli might have been derived from it.<ref name="hemingwayp2" /><ref name="hobsonjobson" /> A few other scholars feel that the name Tiruchirappalli might have been derived from Tiru-chinna-palli meaning "holy little town".<ref name="hemingwayp2" /><ref name="hobsonjobson" /> Some even feel that Tiruchirappali might have been named after a [[Jain]] monk named "Chira".<ref name="suraguidep89">[[#Sura Guide|Sura Guide]], p 89</ref> The ''Madras Glossary'' gives the root as ''Tiru<U+0107><U+0107>in<U+0101>ppalli'' or the "holy (''tiru'') village (''palli'') of the ''shina'' (''[[Cissampelos pareira]]'') plant".<ref name="hobsonjobson" />

During British rule, Tiruchirappalli was commonly referred to using the erroneous spelling "Trichinopoly".<ref name="fallinggrain">{{cite web|title=Tiruchirappalli|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/25/Tiruchchirappalli.html|publisher=Falling Grain genomics Inc.|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> The shortened forms "Trichy"<ref name="frommersindiap350" /><ref name="lonelyplanetp1073">[[#Bindloss and Singh|Bindloss and Singh]], pp 1073</ref><ref name="indiap720">{{cite book|title=India - A Travel Guide|page=720|first1=Dr. B.R.|last1=Kishore|first2=Dr. Shiv|last2=Sharma|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd.|id=ISBN 81-284-0067-3, ISBN 978-81-284-0067-4}}</ref> or "Tiruchi"<ref name="indiap720" /> are more frequently used in common parlance.

==History==
{{See also|History of Tiruchirappalli}}
Tiruchirappalli is one of the oldest inhabited cities in [[Tamil Nadu]]. Situated on the banks of [[Kaveri River]], Tiruchirappalli, was the citadel of the Early Cholas.<ref name="lonelyplanetp411">[[#Bindloss and Singh|Bindloss and Singh]], pp 411</ref> It is mentioned by [[Ptolemy]] in the 2nd century BC.<ref name="footprintp125" /> The earliest settlements date back to the 2nd millennium BC. Sir William Larke, Director of the British Iron and Steel Federation, stated:{{Quotation|The centre of origin is variously placed in India, where there are historical traditions and remains indicating a highly developed iron culture. [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] and Trichinopoly are considered by many to have been the centers of production of wootz... This steel was noted for centuries, being carried by merchants from India to [[Damascus]] and Toledo.." Sir William gives the date of this origin of the [[Iron Age]] as 1400 to 1500 B.C.E",<ref name="tamilculturep324">{{cite book|title=Tamil Culture, Volume 6|page=324|publisher=Academy of Tamil culture|year=1957}}</ref>}}

[[Uraiyur]], which served as the capital of the Early Cholas from the 3rd century BC to the 3rd century AD is a suburb of present-day Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /> The world's oldest surviving dam, the [[Kallanai]], was built by [[Karikala Chola]] across the [[Kaveri River]], about {{convert|24|km|mi}} from [[Uraiyur]].<ref name="limcabookp73">{{cite book|title=Limca Book of records|page=73|year=1990|publisher=Bisleri Beverages}}</ref><ref name="prideofindiap102">{{cite book|title=Pride of India: a glimpse into India's scientific heritage|page=102|first1=R.M.|last1=Pujari|first2=Pradeep|last2=Kolhe|first3=N. R.|last3=Kumar|publisher=Samskrita Bharathi|year=2006|id=ISBN 8187276274, ISBN 9788187276272}}</ref> 

[[File:Tiruchirapalli1955.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Map of Tiruchirappalli town in 1955]]
The medieval history of Tiruchirappalli begins with the reign of the Pallava king [[Mahendravarman I]] who ruled over South India in the 6th century AD.<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /> Mahendravarman constructed the cave-temples within the ''[[Rockfort]]''.<ref name="indiaagesp105">{{cite book|title=	India through the ages: history, art, culture, and religion, Volume 1|page=105|first=G.|last=Kuppuram|publisher=Sundeep Prakashan|year=1998}}</ref> Following the demise of the Pallavas in the 8th century AD, Tiruchirappalli was conquered by the [[Medieval Cholas]] who ruled till the 13th century AD.<ref name="lonelyplanetp1073" />

When the Chola Empire began to decline, Tiruchirappalli was conquered by the Pandyas<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /><ref name="aiyangarp45">[[#Aiyangar|Aiyangar]], p 45</ref> who ruled from 1216 to 1311 when they were defeated by [[Malik Kafur]].<ref name="aiyangarp99">[[#Aiyangar|Aiyangar]], p 99</ref> The victorious armies of the [[Delhi Sultanate]] are believed to have plundered and ravaged the kingdom.<ref name="srirangam">{{cite web|title=A brief history of the Srirangam Temple|url=http://www.ramanuja.org/sv/temples/srirangam/|first=V. S.|last=Seshadri|publisher=Ramanuja.org|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref><ref name="aiyangarp99" /><ref name="aiyangarsrirangam">[[#Aiyangar|Aiyangar]], p 112-116</ref> According to a local legend, the idol of the Hindu god [[Ranganatha]] in the temple of [[Srirangam]] was saved from destruction by burying it under a ''[[bilva]]'' tree.<ref name="essentialhinduismp200">{{cite book|title=Essential Hinduism|page=200|first=Steven|last=Rosen|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|id=ISBN 0275990060, ISBN 9780275990060|year=2006}}</ref><ref name="aiyangarsrirangam" /> Tiruchirappalli was ruled by the Delhi and [[Madurai Sultanate|Madurai]] sultanates from 1311 to 1378 when it was  annexed by the [[Vijayanagar Empire]].<ref name="aiyangarp169">[[#Aiyangar|Aiyangar]], p 169</ref> Tiruchirappalli remained a part of the [[Vijayanagar Empire]]<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /> and its successor, the [[Madurai Nayaks|Madurai Nayak kingdom]] till 1736.<ref name="madurainayaksp234">[[#Sathianathaier|Sathianathaier]], p 234</ref> It served as the capital of the Madurai Nayak kingdom from 1616<ref name="madurainayaksp103">[[#Sathianathaier|Sathianathaier]], p 103</ref> to 1634<ref name="madurainayaksp113">[[#Sathianathaier|Sathianathaier]], p 113</ref> and from 1665<ref name="madurainayaksp160">[[#Sathianathaier|Sathianathaier]], p 160</ref> to 1736. In 1736, the last Madurai Nayak ruler [[Meenakshi (Nayak queen)|Meenakshi]] committed suicide and Tiruchirappalli was conquered by [[Chanda Sahib]]<ref name="madurainayaksp234" /> who ruled the kingdom from 1736 to 1741 when he was captured and imprisoned by the [[Marathas]].<ref name="p52">[[#Subramanian| Subramanian]], p 52</ref><ref name="p53">[[#Subramanian|K. R. Subramanian]], p 53</ref> Tiruchirappalli was administered by the Maratha general [[Murari Rao]] from 1741 to 1743, when it was annexed to the Carnatic kingdom.<ref name="p53" /> When the [[Nawab of the Carnatic]] [[Muhammed Ali Khan Wallajah]] was dethroned by Chanda Sahib in the year 1751, he fled to Tiruchirappalli and set up his base there.<ref name="moderindiap222">{{cite book|title=A history of modern India, 1480-1950|page=222|first=Claude|last=Markovits|publisher=Anthem Press|year=2004|id=ISBN 1843311526, ISBN 9781843311522}}</ref> The subsequent siege of Tiruchirappalli by Chanda Sahib led to the [[Second Carnatic War]].<ref name="moderindiap222" />

At the end of the Second Carnatic War, the kingdom was eventually restored to Muhammed Ali Khan Wallajah who was later forced to cede Tiruchirappalli to the [[British East India Company]] for non-payment of dues.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p29">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 29</ref> The district of [[Trichinopoly District (Madras Presidency)|Trichinopoly]] was constituted in 1801 with the city of Trichinopoly or Tiruchirappalli as its capital and John Wallace as its first District Collector.<ref name="moorep178">[[#Moore|Moore]], p 178</ref>

During the [[Company Raj]] and later, the [[British Raj]], Tiruchirappalli emerged as one of the most important cities in India. It was popular throughout the [[British Empire]] for its unique variety of ''[[cheroot]]'' known as the [[Trichinopoly cigar]].<ref name="hobsonjobson_tritchies">{{cite book|title=Hobson-Jobson: A glossary of colloquial Anglo-Indian words and phrases|chapter=Trichies, Tritchies|url=http://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.2:1:367.hobson|publisher=J. Murray|year=1903|first1=Sir Henry|last1=Yule|authorlink1=Sir Henry Yule|first2=Arthur Coke|last2=Burnell|authorlink2=Arthur Coke Burnell|page=938}}</ref> According to the [[Indian census|1871 Indian census]], the first in British India, Tiruchirappalli had a population of 76,530 making it the second largest city in [[Madras Presidency]], next only to the capital city of [[Madras]].<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p43">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 43</ref>

In the early 20th century, Tiruchirappalli grew further achieving a decadal population growth rate of 36.9 percent during the period 1941-51.<ref name="urbansociologyp193">{{cite book|title=Urban Sociology in India|page=193|id=ISBN 0861252969, ISBN 9780861252961|first=M. S. A.|last=Rao|publisher=Orient Blackswan}}</ref> However, following India's independence, Tiruchirappalli has fallen behind other cities as [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]]<ref name="urbanisationtrendsp148">{{cite book|title=Trends in urbanisation in India, 1901-1981|page=148|first=Raj|last=Bala|publisher=Rawat Publications|year=1986|id=ISBN 8170330122, ISBN 9788170330127}}</ref><ref name="rajendranp3">[[#Rajendran|Rajendran et al]], p3</ref> and [[Coimbatore]]<ref name="thehindu_20110409">{{cite news|title=City of choice|work=The Hindu Property Plus: Coimbatore|url=http://www.hindu.com/pp/2011/04/09/stories/2011040950120100.htm|date=April 9, 2011|first1=Aruna V.|last1=Iyer|first2=Asha V.|last2=Sridhar|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> in terms of growth. As of 2001, Tiruchirappalli was the fourth largest city in Tamil Nadu after Chennai, Coimbatore and Madurai.<ref name="economictimes_it">{{cite news|title=Trichy: IT infrastructure to pep up property prices|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/property/trichy-it-infrastructure-to-pep-up-property-prices/articleshow/5429292.cms|work=[[Economic Times]]|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>

==Geography and climate==
{{See also|Geography of Tiruchirappalli}}

{{climate chart
