|source=Indian Meteorological Department<ref name="indianmeteo">{{cite web|title=Climatology of Tiruchirappalli|url=http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/tiruchirapalli2.htm|publisher=Indian Meteorological Department|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> For graphing purposes, the precipitation numbers of this graph are at a scale of 1:10.
|float=right}}
[[Image:TrichyCity, KaveriRiver and Srirangam.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A view of Tiruchirappalli city, the [[Kaveri river]] and [[Srirangam Island]] from the top of the ''[[Rockfort]]'']]
Tiruchirappalli is located at {{Coord|10.8050|N|78.6856|E|}}.<ref name="fallinggrain" /> The average elevation is {{convert|88|m|ft}}.<ref name="weatherbase">{{cite web|title=Weather data for Tiruchchirappalli, India|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=44334&refer=|publisher=Canty and Associates LLC|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> It is located almost at the geographic centre of the state of [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref name="southindiap438">{{cite book|title=South India|page=438|first=Sarina|last=Singh|publisher=Lonely Planet|year=2009|id=ISBN 1-74179-155-3, ISBN 978-1-74179-155-6}}</ref> The topology of Tiruchirappalli is almost flat with a few isolated hillocks rising above the surface, the highest of which is the ''[[Rockfort]]''.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p26">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 26</ref><ref name="rajendranp1">[[#Rajendran|Rajendran et al]], p 1</ref> The city spread over an area of {{Convert|146.7|km2}} is situated on the plains between the [[Shevaroy Hills]] to the north and the [[Palni Hills]] to the south and south-west.<ref name="abramp489">[[#Abram|Abram]], p 489</ref> The city is situated at the head of the [[Cauvery Delta]]<ref name="britannicap162">{{cite book|title=Students' Britannica India: M to S : (Miraj to Shastri)., Volume 4|page=162|publisher=Popular Prakashan|year=2000|id=ISBN 0-85229-760-2, ISBN 978-0-85229-760-5}}</ref> which commences {{Convert|16|km}} west of Tiruchirappalli<ref name="insecthormonesp317">{{cite book|title=INSECT HARMONES|first=Pradeep|last=Sharma|publisher=Discovery Publishing House|year=2000|id=ISBN 81-8356-290-6, ISBN 978-81-8356-290-4|year=317}}</ref> where the Cauvery River branches into two streams forming the [[Srirangam Island|island of Srirangam]].<ref name="moorep61">[[#Moore|Moore]], p 61</ref>

The land immediately surrounding the Kaveri is made up of fertile [[alluvial]] soil deposited by the Kaveri and its tributary, the [[Kollidam]].<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p32">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 32</ref>  Further south, the surface is covered by poor-quality [[black soil]].<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p32" /> The alluvial soil is conducible for agriculture and crops such as ''ragi'' ([[finger millet]]) and ''cholam'' ([[maize]]) are grown.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p33">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 33</ref> North-east of Tiruchirappalli runs a belt of [[cretaceous]] rock known as the "[[Trichinopoly Group]]".<ref name="geologicalsurveyp104">{{cite book|title=Memoirs of the Geological Survey of India, Volume 4|page=104|year=1865|publisher=[[Geological Survey of India]]}}</ref> Layers of [[archaean]] rocks, [[granite]] and [[gneiss]] covered by a thin bed of [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomeratic]] [[laterite]] are found to the south-east of the city.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p26" /> The flora of Tiruchirappalli city and its surrounding areas is similar to that of the Cauvery delta.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p27">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 27</ref> [[Cattle]] are found in large numbers in the region.<ref name="madraslandrevenuep33">{{cite book|title=	Reports om the settlement of land revenue|publisher=Madras Board of Revenue|year=1869|page=33}}</ref>

The city is divided into three parts: The [[Tiruchirappalli Cantonment|Cantonment]] area to the south, the temples to the north and the bazaar in the center of the city.<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /> Most of Tiruchirappalli's hotels and government and post offices are situated in the cantonment while most of Tiruchirappalli's temples are located in the north.<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /> The Rockfort and its temple are situated in the center of the city and surrounded by a [[bazaar]].<ref name="lonelyplanetp411" /> Densely-populated industrial and residential areas have recently emerged in the northern part of the city. <ref name="rajendranp3" />Residential areas also cover the southern edge of the city.<ref name="rajendranp3" /> The city is completely surrounded by agricultural fields.<ref name="rajendranp3" /> 

During the summer months of March to May, Tiruchirappalli is extremely hot and dry during daytime.<ref name="moorep88">[[#Moore|Moore]], p 88</ref> However, the evenings are rendered cool by cold winds that blow from the south-east.<ref name="moorep88" /> It is quite sultry during September and October but cool and pleasant from November to February.<ref name="moorep88" /> According to a popular saying, the climate of Tiruchirappalli is "eight months hot and four hotter."<ref name="moorep88" /> 

The city gets its drinking water supply from five headworks on the Cauvery River and 1,470 bore wells linked to 60 service [[reservoirs]] in and around the city.<ref name="wateraid" />

The city is at a distance of {{Convert|325|km}} south-west of [[Chennai]]<ref name="frommersindiap350" /> and {{Convert|402|km}} north of [[Kanniyakumari]] on the National Highway [[NH 45]] and {{Convert|205|km}} south-east of [[Coimbatore]]<ref name="footprintp128" /> and {{Convert|128|km}} west from the [[Bay of Bengal]] coast,<ref name="1971censusp5">{{cite book|title=Census of India, 1971: Tamil Nadu|page=5|publisher=Manager of Publications|year=1979}}</ref> The city of Madurai is situated {{Convert|161|km}} south of Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="footprintp128">[[#Bradnock|Bradnock et al.]], p 128</ref>

==Demographics==
[[File:St. lourdes church.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[St Joseph College Church, Tiruchirappalli]]]]
