* 1961-1991:<ref name="rajendranp3" />
* 1991-2001:<ref name="manorama2007p707" />
}}
According to the 2001 census, the Tiruchirappalli had a population of 752,066 with in the corporation limits at a density of 5,127 persons per km<sup>2</sup>,<ref name="cities_towns">{{cite web|title=Cities, Towns and Provinces of India: Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/India-TamilNadu.html|publisher=Thomas Brinkhoff|year=2010|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref><ref name="manorama2007p707">{{cite book|title=Manorama Yearbook 2007|publisher=Malayala Manorama|year=2007|page=707}}</ref> with 376,125 men (50.01 percent) and 375,941 women(49.99 percent).<ref name="census2001">{{cite web|title=Primary Census Abstract Data of Tamil Nadu|url=http://census2001.tn.nic.in/pca2001.aspx|publisher=Directorate of Census Operations|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref>  The urban agglomeration had a population of 866,354.<ref name="cities_towns" /><ref name="southindiap438" /> Tiruchirappalli metropolitan area constitutes the fourth largest metropolitan area in Tamil Nadu and the 47th in India.<ref name="manorama2007p707" /> 11.41 percent of the population was under six years of age.<ref name="census2001" /> Tiruchirappalli had a literacy rate of 79.62 percent with a male literacy rate of 83 percent and a female literacy rate of 75.46 percent.<ref name="census2001" /> The metropolitan area had an estimated population of 829,537 in 2009.<ref name=slbp3">[[#SLB Results Workshop|SLB Results Workshop]], p3</ref>There are a total of 286 [[slums]] in Tiruchirappalli with a population of about 162,000.<ref name="wateraid">{{cite book|title=Tiruchirappalli shows the way|publisher=Wateraid India|year=2008|url=http://www.wateraid.org/documents/plugin_documents/tiruchirappalli_shows_the_way.pdf|page=4|accessdate=2011-05-13}}</ref>

The population is predominantly [[Hindu]], and there are sizable numbers of [[Christians]]<ref name="1971censusp88">{{cite book|title=Census of India, 1971: Tamil Nadu|first=K.|last=Chockalingam|page=88|publisher=Government of India|year=1979}}</ref> and [[Muslims]].<ref name="thehindu_20081210">{{cite news|title=Bakrid celebrated in Trichy with gaiety|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/12/10/stories/2008121059380300.htm|work=The Hindu|date=December 10, 2008|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> [[Sikhs]]<ref name="thehindu_20101229">{{cite news|title=Lt. Governor felicitated|work=The Hindu|date=December 29, 2010|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/12/29/stories/2010122964040300.htm|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> and [[Jains]]<ref name="thehindu_20110407">{{cite news|title=Jain Sangh celebrates Mahaveer Jayanthi|work=The Hindu|date=April 17, 2011|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/04/17/stories/2011041750960200.htm|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>  are also present in smaller numbers. The most widely spoken language is [[Tamil language|Tamil]],<ref name="tourisminindiap606">{{cite book|title=Tourism in India|page=606|author=Ajoy Kumar Sen|publisher=Modern Book Agency|year=1991}}</ref> though there are also significantly large numbers of people speaking [[Telugu language|Telugu]],<ref name="teluguassocp116">{{cite book|title=Directory of Telugu associations outside Andhra Pradesh|page=116|first1=M.|last1=Ramappa|first2=Sudershan|last2=Singh|publisher=International Telugu Institute|year=1984}}</ref> [[Saurashtra language|Saurashtrian]]<ref name="unwritten">{{cite news|title=The Unwritten History of the Saurashtrians of South India|first=T. A.|last=Ramesh|url=http://www.boloji.com/history/039.htm|date=January 15, 2006|publisher=boloji.com}}</ref> and [[Kannada language|Kannada]] <ref name="karnatakaiii">{{cite book|title=History of Karnataka: history, administration & culture|pages=iii|first=I. M.|last=Muthanna|year=1962|publisher=Usha Press}}</ref>  The standard dialect of Tamil spoken is the [[Central Tamil dialect]].<ref name="dravidianp264">{{cite book|title=Dravidian case system, Volume 1|page=264|publisher=Annamalai University|year=1976}}</ref><ref name="langvariations">{{cite web|title=Language Variation in Tamil|url=http://www.lisindia.net/Tamil/Tamil_vari.html|publisher=Language Information Service|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> Saurashtrian is the mother tongue of the ''[[Patn<U+016B>lkarar]]s'' who migrated from Gujarat in the 16th century AD.<ref name="thurstonp123">{{cite book|title=Provincial Geographies of India Vol 4: The Madras Presidency with Mysore, Coorg and Associated States|last=Thurston|first=Edgar|authorlink=Edgar Thurston|publisher=Cambridge University|year=1913|page=123}}</ref> There is also a substantial population of [[Sri Lankan Tamil people|Sri Lankan Tamil migrants]], most of whom are housed in refugee camps on the outskirts of the city.<ref name="thehindu_20091103">{{cite news|title=Sri Lankan Tamil refugees wish for Indian citizenship|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/states/tamil-nadu/article42734.ece|work=The Hindu|date=November 3, 2009|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> There are also sizeable populations of [[Gujaratis]] and [[Marwaris]] resident in the city.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p36">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 36</ref> Most Muslims in the city are [[Labbays]].<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p31">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 31</ref> [[Roman Catholics]] in Tiruchirappalli are affiliated to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tiruchirapalli]]<ref name="cbci">{{cite web|title=Tiruchirapalli Diocese - History|publisher=Catholic Bishops Conference of India|url=http://www.cbcisite.com/Tiruchirapalli.htm|date=2011-05-12}}</ref> while [[Protestants]] are affiliated to the [[Trichy-Tanjore Diocese]] of the [[Church of South India]].<ref name="anglicancommunion">{{cite web|title=Provincial Directory: Trichy-Tanjore|url=http://www.anglicancommunion.org/tour/diocese.cfm?Idind=505|publisher=Anglican Consultative Council|accessdate=2011-05-11}}</ref>

As  a separate division of the [[Southern Railway]] is headquartered at Tiruchirappalli city, there is a considerably strong [[Anglo-Indian]] population in the city.<ref name="anglochroniclesp205">{{cite book|title=The way we were: Anglo-Indian chronicles|page=205|first1=Glenn|last1=Deefholts|first2=Quentine|last2=Acharya|publisher=Calcutta Tiljallah Relief Inc|year=2006|id=ISBN 0975463934, ISBN 9780975463932}}</ref>

== Culture and society ==
{{See also|Tamil culture|Tamil cuisine}}
[[File:Abhishek Raghuram et al 31A.jpg|200px|left|thumb|A [[Carnatic music]] concert]] 

A resident of Tiruchirappalli is generally referred to as a ''Tiruchiite''.<ref name="thehindu_201100320">{{cite news|title=Isha yoga classes give breather to Tiruchiites|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/03/20/stories/2011032062630200.htm|date=March 20, 2011|work=The Hindu|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name="thehindu_20110102">{{cite news|title=City rings in New Year with glitz|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/01/02/stories/2011010255980600.htm|date=January 2, 2011|work=The Hindu|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> The city formed a part of the traditional Chola heartland and has a number of exquisitely-sculpted temples and forts. Situated at the edge of the Cauvery Delta, the culture of Tiruchirappalli is similar to the [[Brahmin|Brahminical culture]] prevalent elsewhere in the delta.<ref name="brahminpriest">{{cite book|title=Brahmin priest of Tamil Nadu|first=K.|last=Subramaniam|publisher=Wiley Eastern|year=1974|id=ISBN 0-85226-848-3, ISBN 97808522684}}</ref> Most internationally known Christian denominations have a presence in the city thereby giving it the name "Rome of the East".<ref name="ttdc">{{cite web|title=TTDC - Places|url=http://www.tamilnadutourism.org/places/citiestowns/Trichy.aspx?catid=010114P01|publisher=Tamil Nadu Tourism Development Corporation Limited|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> With a substantial population of students and migrant industrial workers from different parts of India, Tiruchirappalli has a more cosmopolitan outlook than the surrounding countryside.<ref name="thehindu_20110321">{{cite news|title=Explosion of colours ushers in spring early home|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/03/21/stories/2011032160350200.htm|date=March 21, 2011|work=The Hindu|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name="thehindu_20051225">{{cite news|title=North Indians observe ritual of "Phool Varsha"|url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/25/stories/2005122520130300.htm|work=The Hindu|date=December 25, 2005|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> Tiruchirappalli is home to many Carnatic musicians<ref name="rediff_20081222">{{cite news|title='I learnt Carnatic music as just another subject'|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2008/dec/22trichy-v-pradeep-kumar-carnatic-music.htm|date=December 22, 2008|work=Rediff Movies|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name="anothergarlandp307">{{cite book|title=Another Garland: Biographical Dictionary of Carnatic Composers & Musicians, Book II|first=N.|last=Rajagopalan|year=1992|publisher=Carnatic Classicals|page=307}}</ref> and film artistes.<ref name="asiantribune">{{cite news|title=Birth Centenary of 20th Century's First Super Star Thiyagaraja Bhagavathar|date=March 2, 2010|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/news/2010/03/02/birth-centenary-20th-centurys-first-super-star-thiyagaraja-bhagavathar|work=Asian Tribune|accessdate=2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name="thehindu_20110325">{{cite news|title=Long forgotten maestro|first=Sriram|last=Venkatakrishnan|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2011/03/25/stories/2011032550530200.htm|work=The Hindu|date=March 25, 2011|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref>

Mohini Alangaram, Garuda Sevai, [[Vaikunta Ekadasi]],<ref name="sify_vaikuntaekadasi">{{cite news|title=Vaikuntha Ekadasi celebrations in Trichy|url=http://www.sify.com/news/vaikuntha-ekadasi-celebrations-in-trichy-news-national-kmrnugfgeha.html|date=December 17, 2010|work=Sify|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> flower festival, Srirangam car festival, Teppakulam float festival and the [[Samayapuram Mariamman]] flower festival are some of the important festivals celebrated in Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="suraguidep77">[[#Sura Guide|Sura Guide]], p 77</ref> Festivals like New Year<ref name="thehindu_20110102" /> and [[Christmas]] and other Indian festivals like [[Deepavali]]<ref name="thehindu_20110611">{{cite news|title=Sweet delicacies|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2004/11/06/stories/2004110600530100.htm|work=The Hindu|first=Prathibha|last=Pramaeshwaran|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> and [[Holi]]<ref name="thehindu_20110321" /> are also celebrated with pomp and splendour. There are shopping outlets of handicraft chains ''Khadi Kraft'' and ''Poompuhar'' and bookshop ''[[Higginbotham's]]'', Trichinopoly cigars, [[handicrafts]]. Cheap jewelery made from artificial diamonds are available in the bazaar situated to the immediate north of the Tiruchirappalli railway junction.<ref name="abramp492">[[#Abram|Abram]], p 492</ref> Boxes of [[scotch whisky]] and [[photographic film]] smuggled from [[Sri Lanka]] are also available.<ref name="abramp492" /> The Trichy Travel Federation (TTF) was formed on May 5, 2009 to promote Tiruchirappalli as a favourable tourist destination.<ref name="thehindu_20100813">{{cite news|title=Trichy Travel Federation|date=August 13, 2010|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/08/13/stories/2010081350770200.htm|work=The Hindu|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> 

Both vegetarian and non-vegetarian hotels offering traditional [[Tamil cuisine]] as well as North Indian dishes are located in Tiruchirappalli city.<ref name="lonelyplanetp1091">{{cite book|title=Lonely Planet India: Country Guide Series|first1=Sarina|last1=Singh|first2=Lindsay|last2=Brown|first3=Mark|last3=Elliott|first4=Paul|last4=Harding|first5=Abigail|last5=Hole|first6=Patrick|last6=Horton|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|year=2009|id=ISBN 1741791510, ISBN 9781741791518|page=1091}}</ref> [[Namma Veedu Vasanta Bhavan|Vasanta Bhavan]], a leading food chain originated in Tiruchirappalli in 1969.<ref name="vasantabhavan">{{cite web|title=History of Vasanta Bhavan|url=http://www.vasantabhavan.in/aboutus.php|publisher=Vasanta Bhavan|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref>

==Economy==
{{See Also|Economy of Tiruchirappalli}}
The economy of Tiruchirappalli is mainly industrial. During British rule, the city was known for its [[tanneries]], cigar-manufacturing units and oil presses.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p36">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 36</ref> At its peak, over 12 million cigars were manufactured and exported annually.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p36" /> Tanned hides and skins from Tiruchirappalli were exported to the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p36" />  

The city has a number of retail and wholesale markets, the chief among them being the 128-year old Gandhi market which is an important source of vegetables<ref name="thehindu_20101228">{{cite news|title=Arrival of onions from Maharashtra stabilizes price|work=The Hindu|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/12/28/stories/2010122854770800.htm|first=Syed Muthathar|last=Saqaf|date=December 28, 2010|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> for the whole region.<ref name="thehindu_20100601">{{cite news|title=Market to be shifted|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/06/01/stories/2010060158570100.htm|work=The Hindu|date=June 1, 2010|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name="trichytourism">{{cite web|title=Trichy a land of tradition|url=http://www.tn.gov.in/trichytourism/otherother.htm|publisher=Government of Tamil Nadu|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> Other notable markets in the city are the flower bazaar in [[Srirangam]]<ref name="trichytourism" /> and the [[mango]] market at [[Mambazha Salai]].<ref name="thehindu_20050504">{{cite news|title=Bitter fall in mango prices, thanks to huge arrivals |url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/05/04/stories/2005050415600300.htm|work=The Hindu|date=May 4, 2005|first=M.|last=Balaganessin|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>

Tiruchirappalli is a major engineering equipment manufacturing hub in [[Tamil Nadu]]. The [[Golden Rock Locomotive Workshops]], moved to Tiruchirappalli from [[Nagapattinam]] in 1928, is one of the three [[railway locomotive]] manufacturing units in Tamil Nadu.<ref name="colonialismp126">{{cite book|title=Children of Colonialism: Anglo-Indians in a Postcolonial World|page=126|first=Lionel|last=Caplan|publisher=Berg Publishers|year=2003|id=ISBN 1859736327, ISBN 9781859736326}}</ref> The workshops produced 650 conventional and low-container flat wagons during the year 2007-08.<ref name="goldenrock_thehindu20080411">{{cite news|title=Golden Rock railway workshop rolls out stainless steel wagon prototype|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/04/11/stories/2008041156540200.htm|first=P.|last=Rajaram|work=The Hindu|date=April 11, 2008|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> The chief workshop manager's office at Golden Rock was awarded a star rating by the Bureau of Energy Efficiency for the proper and regulated usage of electricity in its offices.<ref name="toi_20101216">{{cite news|title=Southern Railway to launch new generation locomotive to save power|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Southern-Railway-to-launch-new-generation-locomotive-to-save-power-/articleshow/7108514.cms|date=December 16, 2010|work=Times of India|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>

A High Pressure Boiler manufacturing plant was set up by the [[Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited]] (BHEL), India's largest public sector engineering company, in May 1965.<ref name="casestudiesp71">{{cite book|title=Case Studies In Marketing: The Indian Context 4Th Ed|author=Srinivasan|publisher=PHI Learning Pvt. Ltd.|id=ISBN 81-203-3543-0, ISBN 978-81-203-3543-1|page=71|chapter=Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited}}</ref><ref name="inflationp122">{{cite book|title=Inflation accounting practices in India's corporate sector|first=Mohd Rizwan|last=Ahmad|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distributors|year=2003|id=ISBN 81-269-0216-7, ISBN 978-81-269-0216-3|page=122}}</ref> This was followed by a Seamless Steel Plant set up at a cost of {{INR}}58 [[crore]] ([[US$]]13 million) and a Boiler Auxiliaries Plant. The three manufacturing units  constitute the BHEL industrial complex and cover a total area of about {{Convert|22,927.4|m2|ft2}}. The plant can generate up to 6.2 MW of electricity using coal as a resource.<ref name="bioenergyp19">{{cite book|title=Bio-energy for rural energisation: proceedings of the National Bio-Energy Convention-95 on Bio-Energy for Rural engergisation, organised by Bio-Energy Society of India, during December 4<U+2013>15, 1995 at I.I.T. New Delhi|first1=R. C.|last1=Maheshwari|first2=Pradeep|last2=Chaturvedi|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|year=1997|page=19|id=ISBN 81-7022-670-8, ISBN 978-81-7022-670-3}}</ref> Other important industries in Tiruchirappalli include the Trichy Distilleries and Chemicals Limited (TDCL) which was established at [[Senthaneerpuram]] in the then [[Golden Rock, Tiruchirappalli|Golden Rock municipality]] in the year 1966.<ref name="madrasdistp553">{{cite book|title=Madras District Gazetteers: Tiruchirappalli (pt. 1-2)|page=553|year=1998|publisher=Superintendent, Government Press}}</ref> and the Trichy Steel Rolling Mills which was started as a private limited company on June 27, 1961.<ref name="madrasdistp539">{{cite book|title=Madras District Gazetteers: Tiruchirappalli (pt. 1-2)|page=539|year=1998|publisher=Superintendent, Government Press}}</ref> The Trichy Distilleries and Chemicals Limited manufactures [[rectified spirit]],<ref name="madrasdistp553"/> [[acetaldehyde]],<ref name="madrasdistp553" /> [[acetic acid]],<ref name="madrasdistp553" /> [[acetic anhydride]]<ref name="narcotip56">{{cite book|title=Manufacture of Narcotic Drugs, Psychotropic Substances and Their Precursors|page=56|publisher=United Nations Publications|id=ISBN 92-1-048082-1, ISBN 978-92-1-048082-6}}</ref> and [[ethyl acetate]]. It is one of the biggest private sector distilleries in Tamil Nadu and produced 13.5 million litres of [[Distilled beverage|spirit alcohol]] between December 2005 and November 2006.<ref name="gov_prohibition">{{cite web|title=Demand No. 37: Prohibition and Excise|publisher=Home, Prohibition and Excise Department|page=12|url=http://www.tn.gov.in/policynotes/archives/policy2007-08/pdf/prohibition_excise.pdf|year=2007-08|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> A weapon manufacturing unit<ref name="oft">{{cite web|url=http://ofbindia.nic.in/units/index.php?unit=oft |title=Indian Ordnance Factories: Ordnance Factory Tiruchirapalli |publisher=Ordnance Factory Board, Defence Ministry, Government of India|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> and a [[Heavy Alloy Penetrator Project]] (HAPP) facility<ref name="happ">{{cite web|title=Indian Ordnance Factories: Heavy Alloy Penetrator Project|url=http://ofbindia.nic.in/units/index.php?unit=happ|publisher=Ordnance Factory Board, Defence Ministry, Government of India|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> are run by the Ordnance Factory Board of the Government of India.<ref name="powdermetallurgyp50">{{cite book|title=Powder metallurgy: processing for automotive, electrical/electronic and engineering industry ; [International Conference on Powder Metallurgy for Automotive and Engineering Industry ... at the Renaissance Mumbai Hotel and Convention Center during Feb. 3 - 6, 2005]|page=50|first=P.|last=Ramakrishnan|publisher=New Age International|year=2007|id=ISBN 8122420303, ISBN 9788122420302}}</ref> The HAPP unit, set up in the late 1980s, comprises of a [[Flexible manufacturing system]] (FMS), the first of its kind in India.<ref name="cadp656">{{cite book|title=Cad/cam/cim|first=P.|last=Radhakrishnan|publisher=New Age International|year=2000|id=ISBN 8122412483, ISBN 9788122412482|page=656}}</ref>

[[EID Parry]]'s sugar factory at [[Pettavaithalai]]<ref name="eidparry">{{cite web|title=Divisions of EID Parry (India) Limited|url=http://www.eidparry.com/divisions.asp|publisher=E.I.D. Parry (India) Ltd.|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> and [[Dalmia Group]] cement factory at [[Dalmiapuram]] are some major manufacturing units located on the outskirts of Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="thehindu_20100206">{{cite news|title=Dalmia Cement to finalize revamp plan by March end|first=R.|last=Balaji|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2010/02/06/stories/2010020652530200.htm|work=The Hindu: Business Line|date=February 6, 2010|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> 

The annual software exports of the Tiruchi region amount to {{INR}}26.21 [[crore]] ([[US$]]5.8 million).<ref name="economictimes_it" /> The ELCOT IT Park, the first IT park in the city has been commissioned at a cost of {{INR}}60 [[crore]] ([[US$]]13.5 million) and inaugurated by the Deputy Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu, [[M. K. Stalin]] on December 9, 2010.<ref name="thehindu_tiruchiitcomm">{{cite news|title=Tiruchi IT Park commissioned|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/12/10/stories/2010121061490100.htm|work=The Hindu|date=December 10, 2010|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name="thehindu_itpark">{{cite news|title=Tiruchi gets IT park|date=December 10, 2010|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/12/10/stories/2010121059100100.htm|work=The Hindu|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> Set up by the Electronics Corporation of Tamil Nadu, the park occupies an area of {{Convert|59.74|ha|acre}} and constitutes a [[Special Economic Zone]].<ref name="thehindu_itpark" /><ref name="thehindu_20080719">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/07/19/stories/2008071953840500.htm |title=Tamil Nadu / Tiruchi News : ELCOT to build 50,000 sq.ft. of office space in Tier II cities |work=The Hindu |date=July 19, 2008|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> The Indian software company [[Infosys]], is planning to start its operations in Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="economictimes_20090728">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2009-07-28/news/27653675_1_tier-ii-software-major-infosys-managing-director-s-gopalakrishnan |title=Infosys eyeing Tier-II cities for expansion - Economic Times |work=[[Economic Times]] |date=July 28, 2009|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>

==Transport==
[[File:Trichy05.JPG|thumb|200px|Train waiting at the [[Tiruchirappalli Junction]]]]
{{Main|Transport in Tiruchirappalli}}
Tiruchirappalli is well connected by road, rail and air with most cities and towns in India.<ref name="indianstatesp19">{{cite book|title=Indian states at a glance, 2008-09: Tamil Nadu : performance, facts and figures|first=Laveesh|last=Bhandari|publisher=Pearson Education|page=19|id=ISBN 813172347X, ISBN 9788131723470|year=2009}}</ref><ref name="frommersindiap351">{{cite book|title=Frommer's India|page=351|first1=Pippa|last1=de Bruyn|first2=Keith|last2=Bain|first3=David|last3=Allardice|id=ISBN 0-470-55610-2, ISBN 978-0-470-55610-8|publisher=Frommer's|year=2010}}</ref> The [[National Highway (India)|National Highways]] [[NH 45]], [[NH 45B]], [[NH 67]], [[NH 210]] and [[NH 227]] pass through the city.<ref name=NHAI>{{cite web|title=National Highways passing through Trichy|url=http://www.nhai.org/Doc/project-offer/Highways.pdf|publisher=National Highways Authority of India|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> Tiruchirappalli forms a part of the Division no. 1 of the [[Tamil Nadu State Transport Corporation]] which is headquartered at [[Kumbakonam]].<ref name="cholanroadways">{{cite web|title=Tamil Nadu State Transport Corporation (KUM DIV-I) Ltd., Kumbakonam|url=http://www.tn.gov.in/transport/kumdivone.htm|publisher=Government of Tamil Nadu|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> There are regular buses to [[Thanjavur]],<ref name="footprintp128" /> [[Pudukkottai]],<ref name="footprintp128" /> [[Kanniyakumari]],<ref name="footprintp128" />  [[Chennai]],<ref name="footprintp128" /> [[Madurai]],<ref name="footprintp128" /> [[Palani]],<ref name="footprintp128" /> [[Puducherry]],<ref name="abramp491">[[#Abram|Abram]], p 491</ref> [[Coimbatore]],<ref name="footprintp128" /> [[Kodaikanal]]<ref name="footprintp128" /> and [[Tirupati (city)|Tirupathi]].<ref name="footprintp128" /> Buses are also available to destinations in [[Karnataka]] and [[Kerala]]. The [[Karnataka State Road Transport Corporation]] (KSRTC) operates special bus services between [[Bangalore]] and Tiruchirapalli during weekends.<ref name="ksrtc_news">{{cite web|title=News|url=http://www.ksrtc.in/News.html|publisher=Karnataka State Road Transport Corporation|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> There are two major bus termini: the Chathram Bus Stand and the Central Bus Station,<ref name="footprintp128" /> both situated close to each other.<ref name="abramp491" /> The bus termini are situated at a distance of {{Convert|1|km}} from the main railway station.<ref name="footprintp128" /> The city has an efficient local bus transportation system - both government-operated as well as private.<ref name="abramp491" />
[[Image:Trichyairportfront.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The [[Tiruchirapalli Airport]] is the second most busiest airport in Tamil Nadu]]
The Great Southern of India Railway Company was established in 1853 with its headquarters at Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="muthiahp321">{{cite book | title=Madras Rediscovered| last=Muthiah| first=S.|authorlink=S. Muthiah |year=2004| page=321| publisher=East West Books (Madras) Pvt Ltd| isbn=81-88661-24-4}}</ref> In 1859, the company constructed its first railway line connecting Tiruchirappalli and Nagapattinam.<ref name="muthiahp321" /> Currently, Tiruchirappalli is an important railway junction in central Tamil Nadu and constitutes a separate division of the [[Southern Railway (India)|Southern Railway]].<ref name="trichydivision">{{cite web|title=Tiruchchirappalli division|url=http://www.sr.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,263,579,582|publisher=[[Southern Railway (India)|Southern Railway]]|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> There are frequent trains to Chennai, Madurai, [[Chidambaram]], [[Bangalore]], [[Rameswaram]], [[Mangalore]], Tirupathi, [[Kolkata]], [[Guwahati]] and [[Cochin]].<ref name="templesindiap144">{{cite book|title=Temples of South India|first=Ambujam|last=Anantharaman|page=144|publisher=East West Books (Madras)|year=2006|id=ISBN 8188661422, ISBN 9788188661428}}</ref> There are nine daily express trains operating on the Chennai-Tiruchirappalli line, important among which are [[Vaigai Express]], [[Pallavan Express]] and the [[Rockfort Express]].<ref name="lonelyplanetp415">[[#Bindloss and Singh|Bindloss and Singh]], p 415</ref> The [[Mysore Express]] plies between Tiruchirappalli and [[Mysore]] on a daily basis, stopping at [[Bangalore]] on the way.<ref name="lonelyplanetp415" /> Tiruchirappalli has rail connectivity with most important cities and towns in India.<ref name="indianstatesp19" />

The [[Tiruchirapalli International Airport]] is the second biggest airport in Tamil Nadu in terms of passenger traffic, cargo traffic as well as aircraft movement.<ref name="position">{{cite web|title=Indian Airports: Existing Position|url=http://civilaviation.nic.in/aai/airport.htm#EXISTING|publisher=Airports Authority of India|accessdate=2010-10-02}}</ref> It was first used to handle air traffic in 1938 when [[Tata Airlines]] commercial flights stopped at Tiruchirappalli on the [[Karachi]]-[[Colombo]] route.<ref name="airindia_history_1930s">{{cite web|url=http://home.airindia.in/SBCMS/Webpages/Time-line-1932-1940.aspx?MID=196|title=History 1932-1940|publisher=Air India|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> In 1948, [[Air Ceylon]] commenced daily passenger flights between Tiruchirappalli and Colombo via Jaffna.<ref name="economicreviewp48">{{cite book|title=Far Eastern economic review, Volumes 71-72|page=48|publisher=Review Pub. Co. Ltd.|year=1971}}</ref><ref name="commonwealthsurveyp24">{{cite book|title=Commonwealth survey, Volumes 1-2|year=1948|page=24|publisher=Central Office of Information by Her Majesty's Stationery Office}}</ref> There are regular flights to Chennai,<ref name="lonelyplanetp415" /> [[Kochi]],<ref name="abramp489" /> [[Kozhikode]],<ref name="abramp491" /> Sri Lanka,<ref name="suraguidep78">[[#Sura Guide|Sura Guide]], p 78</ref> [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]]<ref name="suraguidep78" /> and [[Kuwait]].<ref name="suraguidep78" />

==Administration and politics==
{{See also|Tiruchirappalli Municipal Corporation}}
