The [[municipality]] of Tiruchirappalli was inaugurated under the Town Improvements Act 1865 on November 1, 1866 covering an area of {{convert|18|km2|mi2}}<ref name="trichinopolyp13">{{cite book|title=Report upon the military and civil station of Trichinopoly|first=J. L.|last=Ranking|year=1867|page=13}}</ref> and originally consisted of two ex-officio and nine nominated members.<ref name="hemingwayp263">[[#Hemingway|Hemingway]], p 263</ref> Elections to the council were introduced in 1877 and the first chairman was elected in 1889.<ref name="hemingwayp263" /> The municipality was upgraded to a [[municipal corporation]] as per the Tiruchirappalli City Municipal Corporation Act 1994<ref name="panchayatirajp80">{{cite book|title=A handbook for panchayati raj administration (Tamil Nadu)|page=80|first=Ganapathy|last=Palanithurai|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|year=2007|id=ISBN 81-8069-340-6, ISBN 978-81-8069-340-3}}</ref> by inclusion of the [[Srirangam]] and Golden Rock municipalities.<ref name="districtgazetteersp1297">{{cite book|title=Madras District Gazetteers: Tiruchirappalli (pts. 1-2)|page=1297|first=B. S.|last=Baliga|publisher=Superintendent, Govt. Press|year=1999}}</ref> The municipal corporation currently covers an area of {{convert|146.7|km2|mi2}} and comprises 60 wards and four administrative zones: [[Srirangam]], [[Ariyamangalam]], [[Golden Rock, Tiruchirappalli|Golden Rock]] and [[Abhishekapuram]].<ref name="townplanning">{{cite web|title=Town Planning Department|url=http://www.trichycorporation.gov.in/town.php|publisher=Tiruchirappalli City Municipal Corporation|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>
[[Image:Trichycorporation.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Tiruchirappalli Municipal Corporation building]]

The Tiruchirappalli City Municipal Corporation Council, the legislative body, comprises 60 councilors elected from each of the 60 wards and is headed by a [[mayor]] assisted by a [[Deputy Mayor]].<ref name="citymunc">{{cite web|title=About city municipal corporation|url=http://www.trichycorporation.gov.in/aboutc.php#menu|publisher=Tiruchirappalli City Municipal Corporation|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> The executive wing is made up of seven departments: General administration, revenue, town planning, engineering, public health, information technology and personnel and is headed by a City Commissioner. The Commissioner is assisted by two executive engineers for the east and west sections, and Assistant Commissioners for personnel, accounts and revenue departments, a public relations officer, a city engineer, a city health officer and an Assistant Commissioner for each of the four zones.<ref name="orgchart">{{cite web|title=Organizational chart|url=http://www.trichycorporation.gov.in/orgchart.php#menu|publisher=Tiruchirappalli City Municipal Corporation|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>

The city of Tiruchirappalli is represented in the [[Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly]] by four elected members, one each for the [[Tiruchirappalli - I (State Assembly Constituency)|Tiruchirappalli <U+2013> I]], [[Tiruchirappalli <U+2013> II (State Assembly Constituency)|Tiruchirappalli <U+2013> II]], [[Srirangam (State Assembly Constituency)|Srirangam]] and [[Thiruverambur (State Assembly Constituency)|Tiruverumbur]] constituencies.<ref name="assemblyconstituencymap">{{cite web|title=Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly Constitutency map|url=http://www.assembly.tn.gov.in/Const_map/map.htm|publisher=[[Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly]]|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref name="const_map">{{cite web|title=Map showing the new assembly constituencies|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/maps/tamil_map.pdf|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> Tiruchirappali is also a part of the [[Tiruchirappalli (Lok Sabha constituency)|Tiruchirappalli Lok Sabha constituency]] and elects a member to the [[Lok Sabha]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of India]], once every five years.<ref name="const_map" /><ref>{{cite web
| url = http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2001/background/S22/TN_ACPC.pdf|format=PDF| title = List of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies| work = Tamil Nadu| publisher = Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref>
The Lok Sabha seat has been held by the [[Indian National Congress]] for four terms (1957<U+2013>62,<ref name="1957electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1957/Vol_I_57_LS.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1957 to the Second Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> 1984-89,<ref name="1984electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1984/Vol_I_LS_84.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1984 to the Eighth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> 1989-91<ref name="1989electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1989/Vol_I_LS_89.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1989 to the Ninth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> and 1991-96<ref name="1991electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1991/VOL_I_LS_91.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1991 to the Tenth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref>), the [[Communist Party of India]] for three terms (1962<U+2013>67,<ref name="1962electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1962/Vol_I_LS_62.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1962 to the Third Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> 1971-77<ref name="1971electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1971/Vol_I_LS_71.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1971 to the Fifth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> and 1977-80<ref name="1977electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1977/Vol_I_LS_77.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1977 to the Sixth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref>) and the [[All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]] (2001<U+2013>04 and 2009<U+2013>present<ref name="2009elections">{{cite book|title=Notification No. 308/2009/EPS|publisher=Election Commission of India|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/press/ECI_15th_Lok_Sabha.pdf|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref>) and [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (1998-99<ref name="1998electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1998/Vol_I_LS_98.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1998 to the Twelfth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> and 1999-2001<ref name="1999electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1999/Vol_I_LS_99.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1999 to the Thirteenth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref>) for two terms each. Candidates from the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]],<ref name="1967electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1967/Vol_I_LS_67.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1967 to the Fourth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> [[Tamil Maanila Congress (Moopanar)]] and the [[Marumalarchi Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]]<ref name="2004electionresults">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_2004/Vol_I_LS_2004.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 2004 to the Fourteenth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> have won once each. Indian politician [[Rangarajan Kumaramangalam]] who served as the Minister of Power in the government of [[Atal Behari Vajpayee]],<ref name="cabinetberth_rediff">{{cite news|title=Cabinet berth for Kumaramangalam upsets TN BJP|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/mar/30tnbjp.htm|date=March 30, 1998|work=[[Rediff]]|first=N. Sathiya|last=Moorthy|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> was elected to the Lok Sabha from Tiruchirappalli in the 1998 and 1999 elections.<ref name="1998electionresults" /><ref name="1999electionresults" />

Law and order is enforced by the Tamil Nadu police, which, for administrative purposes, has constituted Tiruchirappalli city as a separate district.<ref name="trichypolice">{{cite web|title=Trichy city|url=http://www.tnpolice.gov.in/District_Details.php?code=29620|publisher=Tamil Nadu police|accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref>  The district is divided into eight sub-divisions with a total of 16 police stations. The Tiruchirappalli city police force is headed by a [[Commissioner of police]] assisted by Deputy Commissioners. Law and order enforcement in the suburban areas are handled by the Tiruchirappalli district police.<ref name="trichydistpolice">{{cite web|title=Trichy district|url=http://www.tnpolice.gov.in/District_Details.php?code=29604|publisher=Tamil Nadu police|accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref> As of 2008, Tiruchirappalli had a [[crime rate]] of 459.99 making it the second highest among cities in Tamil Nadu.<ref name="tnpolice_crimes">{{cite web|title=Crimes in cities of Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.tnpolice.gov.in/pdfs/CR_2008/WRITEUPS/2.%20%2017%20-25%20CRIMES%20IN%20CITIES%20OF%20TN.pdf|publisher=Tamil Nadu police}}</ref> However, Tiruchirappalli had the lowest proportion of murder, rape and kidnapping cases.<ref name="tnpolice_crimes" />

==Education==
{{Main|List of educational institutions in Trichy}}
[[File:Nitt.adblock.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Administrative block of the [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]]]]
Even during British rule, Tiruchirappalli was recognized as an important educational centre in India.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p48">[[#Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Vol 24, p 48</ref> [[St. Joseph's College, Tiruchirappalli|St. Joseph's College]], opened in [[Nagapattinam]] in 1846 and transferred to Tiruchirappalli in 1883, is one of the oldest educational institutions in South India.<ref name="catholicencyclopediap41">{{cite book|title=The Catholic encyclopedia: an international work of reference on the constitution, doctrine, discipline, and history of the Catholic Church, Volume 15|page=41|year=1913|first1=Charles George|last1=Herbermann|first2=Edward Aloysius|last2=Pace|first3=Cond<U+00E9> B<U+00E9>noist|last3=Pallen|first4=Thomas Joseph|last4=Shahan|first5=John Joseph|last5=Wynn|publisher=Encyclopedia Press}}</ref> The Society for the Propagation of the Gospel (SPG) college, established in 1883, is another premium missionary institution in the city.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p48" />  

Tiruchirappalli has a total of 27 arts, science and law colleges,<ref name="trichyschoolsandcolleges">{{cite web|title=Schools and colleges: List of schools and colleges|url=http://www.trichycorporation.gov.in/schools_colleges.php#menu|publisher=Tiruchirappalli Municipal Corporation|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> notable ones being the [[National College, Tiruchirapalli|National College]],<ref name="thehindu_20100927">{{cite news|title=Campus Connect: Tiruchirapalli|url=http://www.hindu.com/edu/2010/09/27/stories/2010092750410800.htm|work=The Hindu|date=September 27, 2007|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> [[Bishop Heber College]],<ref name="commonwealthyearbookp737">{{cite book|title=Commonwealth universities yearbook, Volume 1|page=737|publisher=Association of Commonwealth Universities|year=2003}}</ref> [[Jamal Mohamed College]]<ref name="muslimseducationp13">{{cite book|title=Education and Muslims in India since Independence|page=13|first=Abdull<U+0101>h Val<U+012B> Bak<U+0332>h<U+0332>sh|last1=Q<U+0101>dir<U+012B>|first2=Mohd. Akhtar|last2=Siddiqui|publisher=Institute of Objective Studies|year=1998|id=ISBN 8185220522, ISBN 9788185220529}}</ref> and the [[Government Law College, Tiruchirappalli|Government Law College]].<ref name="loksabha2007p350">{{cite book|title=Lok Sabha debates|page=350|year=2007|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat}}</ref>There are also 35 engineering colleges in the city.<ref name="economictimes_it" /><ref name="trichyschoolsandcolleges" /> The [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli|National Institutes of Technology]] have a campus at [[Thuvakudi]] on the outskirts of the city.<ref name="outlook-2009">{{cite journal|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?250245|title=Top 75: Engineering Colleges|journal=Outlook India|date=June 22, 2009|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref name="outlook-2007">{{cite journal|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/full.asp?fodname=20070611&fname=APemchand+Palety&sid=4|title=Top 50 Govt Engineering Colleges|journal=Outlook India|date=June 11, 2007|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref name="dataquest-2005">{{cite journal|url=http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/top_stories/2005/105052101.asp|title=Dataquest-IDC-NASSCOM Survey: India's Best T-Schools|journal=Dataquest|date=May 21, 2005|first=Bhaswati|last=Chakravorty|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> The Tiruchirappalli branch of [[Anna University Trichy|Anna University]] was established following the bifurcation of Anna University in 2007.<ref name="annaunivcbe">{{cite web|url= http://www.annauniv.ac.in/about.aspx|title=About University|publisher=Anna University, Coimbatore|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> A total of 64 self-financing colleges offering courses on [[engineering]], [[architecture]], [[management]] and [[computer applications]] in the districts of [[Ariyalur District|Ariyalur]], [[Cuddalore District|Cuddalore]], [[Nagapattinam District|Nagapattinam]], [[Perambalur District|Perambalur]], [[Pudukkottai District|Pudukkottai]], [[Thanjavur District|Thanjavur]] and [[Tiruvarur District|Tiruvarur]] are affiliated to this University.<ref name="annaunivbifurcation">{{cite web|title=Bifurcation of Anna university|url=http://tau.edu.in/|publisher=Anna university, Trichy|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> The [[SRM Group of Colleges]] established the SRM Institute of Science and Technology at [[Irungalur]] near Tiruchirappalli followed by Chennai Medical College and Hospital in 2007. A proposal by the group to include the institutions in the [[SRM University]] is under review of the Ministry of Human Resources Development of the Government of India.<ref name="toi_20110328">{{cite news|title=SRM varsity a step closer to off-campus centre in Tiruchi|work=Times of India|date=March 28, 2011|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-03-28/chennai/29353695_1_srm-university-ugc-resolution-ugc-guidelines|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>

The [[Bharathidasan University]] is based in Tiruchirappalli and exercises its jurisdiction over colleges in [[Tiruchirappalli district]] and seven neighbouring ones.<ref name="bharathidasanp121">{{cite book|title=Handbook of universities |page=121|first1=Ameeta|last1=Gupta|first2=Ashish|last2=Kumar|id=ISBN 81-269-0607-3, ISBN 978-81-269-0607-9|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distributors|year=2006}}</ref>The university runs a management school, the [[Bharathidasan Institute of Management]] in Tiruchirappalli in collaboration with BHEL.<ref name="thehindu_20090205">{{cite news|title=Shifting of Centre of Distance Education begins|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/02/05/stories/2009020560220600.htm|date=February 5, 2009|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> The Government of India's Ministry for Human Resources Development (HRD) has approved a proposal for the setting up of a campus of the [[Indian Institute of Management]] in Tiruchirappalli and the campus is expected to start functioning from the 2011-12 academic season.<ref name="indianexpress_20100430">{{cite news|title=Now, IIM-Kashipur, IIM-Trichy|work=[[Indian Express]]|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/now-iimkashipur-iimtrichy/613308/|date=April 30, 2010|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref name="livemint_20100520">{{cite news|title=Only two of four new IIMs to start this year|url=http://www.livemint.com/2010/05/20231235/Only-two-of-four-new-IIMs-to-s.html|date=May 20, 2010|work=Live Mint|first=Prashant K.|last=Nanda|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref name="toi_20110211">{{cite news|title=IIM-Trichy to commence operations from June|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-11/india/28548198_1_iim-trichy-prafulla-agnihotri-faculty|date=February 11, 2011|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>

There are a total of 100 government and private schools in Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="trichyschoolsandcolleges" /> The National High School was established in 1886 to counter Christian propaganda in missionary-run schools.<ref name="imperialgazetteer1908v24p48" /> The [[RSK Higher Secondary School]],<ref name="excellencep18">{{cite book|title=The voyage to excellence: the ascent of 21 women leaders of India Inc|page=18|first=Nischinta|last=Amarnath|publisher=[[Pustak Mahal]]|year=2005|id=ISBN 8122309046, ISBN 9788122309041}}</ref> [[Campion Anglo-Indian Higher Secondary School]],<ref name="loksabhap28">{{cite book|title=Lok Sabha debates|page=28|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat|year=1998}}</ref> and [[St. Johns Vestry Anglo Indian Higher Secondary School]]<ref name="colonialcousinsp380">{{cite book|title=Colonial Cousins: A Surprising History of Connections Between India and Australia|page=380|first1=Joyce|last1=Westrip|first2=Peggy|last2=Holroyde|publisher=Wakefield Press|year=2010|id=ISBN 1862548412, ISBN 9781862548411}}</ref><ref name="thehindu_20050802">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/yw/2005/08/26/stories/2005082602460600.htm|title=St. John's Vestry Anglo-Indian Higher Secondary School|date= August 26, 2005|work=The Hindu|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> are some of the notable schools in the city.

==Media==

According to the Registrar of newspapers in India, a total of 111 newspapers have been registered in Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="newspapers-list">{{cite web|url=https://rni.nic.in/search_place.asp|title=Publication Place Wise-Registration|publisher= Registrar of Newspapers for India}}</ref> Among the major English-language newspapers published from Tiruchirappalli are ''[[The Hindu]]'' which launched a Tiruchirappalli edition in 2004<ref name="trichyedition">{{cite news|title=The Hindu soon to launch Trichy edition|first=G.|last=Abitha|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/e4m/news/fullstory_band.asp?news_id=11719&tag=6445&section_id=5|date=April 21, 2004|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref name="thehindu_aboutus">{{cite web|title=About us|publisher=The Hindu|url=http://www.thehindu.com/navigation/?type=static&page=aboutus|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> and ''[[The New Indian Express]]'' which was publishing from Tiruchirappalli even before ''The Hindu''.<ref name="agrip75">{{cite book|title=Agricultural mechanization in Asia, Africa and Latin America: AMA., Volumes 35-37|page=75|year=2004|author=N<U+014D>ki sangy<U+014D> ch<U+014D>sa kenky<U+016B>jo|publisher=Farm Machinery Industrial Research Corp.|year=2004}}</ref> Some of the important Tamil-language newspapers that publish a Tiruchirappalli edition are ''[[Dina Thanthi]]''<ref name="dinathanthi">{{cite web|title=''Dhina Thanthi'' Tiruchi edition Home page|url=http://www.dailythanthi.com/home.asp?EditionID=12|language=Tamil|publisher=Daily Thanthi|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>''[[Dina Mani]]'',<ref name="dinamani">{{cite web|title="Dina Mani" e-newspaper Trichy edition|url=http://www.dinamani.com/edition/subsection.aspx?SectionName=Edition-Trichy&SectionID=138&MainSectionID=134|publisher=Dina Mani|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref>''[[Dina Malar]]'', ''[[Malai Malar]]'', ''[[Dinakaran]]'',<ref name="bennp95">{{cite book|title=Benn's press directory, Volume 2|publisher=Benn's Publications Limited|year=1978|page=95}}</ref>''[[Tamil Murasu]]'' and ''[[Tamil Sudar]]''.<ref name="newspapers-list" /> Popular Tamil weekly ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'' launched a local supplement for Tiruchirappalli on the occasion of the 85th anniversary of its founding.<ref name="thehindu_20110303">{{cite news|title=Vikatan celebrates 85th anniversary|work=The Hindu|date=March 3, 2011|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/03/03/stories/2011030356220400.htm|accessdate=2011-05-22}}</ref>  

The first radio transmission station in Tiruchirappalli was opened by the [[All India Radio]] (AIR) on May 16, 1939.<ref name="broadcastingp118">{{cite book|title=Indian broadcasting|page=118|first=H. R.|last=Luthra|publisher=Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting|year=1986}}</ref><ref name="wirelesswordlp297">{{cite book|title=Wireless world, Volume 53|page=297|year=1947}}</ref> AIR started providing direct-to-home enabled radio broadcasting service from 2006.<ref name="thehindu_20060112">{{cite news|title=Three AIR stations to go DTH by mid-year|work=The Hindu|date=January 12, 2006|url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/01/12/stories/2006011207900500.htm|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>In 2007, the AIR launched a separate Carnatic music channel - Ragam from Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="businessline_20070525">{{cite news|title=AIR launches `Ragam' for DTH audience|first=R.|last=Ravikumar|work=The Hindu: Business Line|date=July 27, 2007|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/2007/05/25/stories/2007052500940500.htm|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref> Apart from the [[Government of India|government]]-owned AIR, private radio channels as Hello FM and [[Suryan FM]] also operate FM stations in Tiruchirappalli.<ref name="asiawaves">{{cite web|first=Venkat|title=FM stations in trichy|url=http://www.asiawaves.net/india/tamil-nadu-radio.htm#tiruchirapalli-radio|publisher=Asiawaves|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> [[Indira Gandhi National Open University]]'s ''Gyan Vani'' started broadcasting from Tiruchirappalli in 2008.<ref name="thehindu_20080907">{{cite news|title=Gyan Vani to be on air from Tiruchi in 3 months|first=R.|last=Krishnamoorthy|work=The Hindu|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/09/07/stories/2008090757310600.htm|date=September 7, 2008|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> Tiruchirappalli's first campus community radio was started by Holy Cross College on December 22, 2006.<ref name="thehindu_20061222">{{cite news|title=Community radio is best suited for fulfilling information needs of villages |work=The Hindu|date=December 22, 2006|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2006/12/22/stories/2006122225180300.htm|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref> 

Television broadcasting from Chennai was started on August 15, 1975.<ref name"thehindu_20091009">{{cite news|title=Celebrating a milestone|work=The Hindu|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/radio-and-tv/article31314.ece|date=October 9, 2009|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref> Satellite television channels have been available from 1991 onwards.<ref name="satellitep58">{{cite book|title=Satellite invasion of India|first=S. C.|last=Bhatt|year=1994|publisher=Gyan Books|id=ISBN 8121204836, ISBN 9788121204835}}</ref> Direct-to-home cable television services are provided by [[DD Direct Plus]]<ref name="thehindu_20041219">{{cite news|title=Demonstration of DTH technology|work=The Hindu|date=December 19, 2004|url=http://www.hindu.com/2004/12/19/stories/2004121904450300.htm|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref><ref name="dth_dealerlist">{{cite web|title=List of Dealers in Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.ddinews.gov.in/DTH/Dealers/TamilNadu.htm|publisher=DD News|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref><ref name="Television relay in Trichy">{{cite web|title=Doordarshan|url=http://www.ddindia.gov.in/About+DD/Doordarshan+Maintenance+Centres|publisher=Doordarshan|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref> and [[Sun Direct DTH]].<ref name="thehindu_20070924">{{cite news|title=STrike hits cable TV services|work=The Hindu|date=September 24, 2007|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/09/24/stories/2007092458660300.htm|accessdate=20}}</ref>

== Utility services ==

Electricity supply to the city is regulated and distributed by the [[Tamil Nadu Electricity Board]] (TNEB).<ref name="tnebtrichy">{{cite web|title=Tamil Nadu Electricity Board - Trichy Region|url=http://www.tneb.in/template_3.php?tempno=&cid=0&subcid=93|publisher=Tamil Nadu Electricity Board|accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref> Tiruchirappalli is the headquarters of the Trichy region of TNEB. The city along with its suburbs forms the Trichy Metro Electricity Distribution Circle which is further sub-divided into six divisions.<ref name="tnebtrichy" /> A Chief Distribution engineer is stationed at the regional headquarters at [[Tennur]].<ref name="tnebtrichy" /> Water supply is provided by the Tiruchirappalli City Corporation.<ref name="waterservices">{{cite web|title=Water supply-Trichy Corporation|url=http://www.trichycorporation.gov.in/watersupply.php|publisher=Tiruchirappalli Municipal Corporation|accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref>Of the six headworks from which the city gets its water supply, four are maintained by the municipal corporation and the rest by other agencies.<ref name="slbp4">[[#SLB Results Workshop|SLB Results Workshop]], p 4</ref> Apart from the  Gandhi market, Central Bus terminus and the Chathram bus terminus, solid waste management in the city is handled by the corporation.<ref name="slbp4" /> About 400 tonnes of solid waste are released from city every year.<ref name="thehindu_20040815">{{cite news|title=Waste management programme begins|work=The Hindu|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2004/08/15/stories/2004081513990300.htm|date=August 15, 2004|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref> The prinicipal garbage dumping ground is at [[Ariyamangalam]].<ref name="thehindu_20100312">{{cite news|title=Corporation to go in for scientific closure of garbage dump|work=The Hindu|first=S.|last=Ganesan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Tiruchirapalli/article236840.ece|date=March 12, 2010|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref>  Recently, the Tiruchirappalli city corporation has gone in for scientific closure of the garbage dump and its replacement with a sewage treatment plant.<ref name="thehindu_20100312" />Waste water management in the Trichy-Srirangam under ground drainage (UGD) areas are handled by the Tamil Nadu Water Supply and Drainage (TWAD) board and in other areas by the Tiruchirappalli Municipal Corporation.<ref name="slbp4" /> The high toxicity of the waste water released by the Trichy Distilleries and Chemicals Limited (TDCL) is a major cause of concern for the corporation.<ref name="environmentalhealthp92">{{cite book|title=Environmental health, Volume 13|page=92|publisher=Central Public Health Engineering Research Institute|year=1991}}</ref>The corporation's annual expenditure for the year 2010-11 is estimated to be Rs. 155.94 crores.<ref name="thehindu_20110129">{{cite news|title=AIADMK, MDMK councillors stage walk-out; allege neglect of wards|work=The Hindu|date=January 29, 2011|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/01/29/stories/2011012961270300.htm|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref>Under the National Urban Sanitation Policy, Tiruchirappalli, with a sanitation coverage of 70 percent was ranked sixth in India and first in Tamil Nadu on the basis of sanitation for the year 2009-10.<ref name="sanitationpolicy">{{cite web|title=Rank of cities on sanitation 2009-10|publisher=National Urban Sanitation Policy|url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2010/may/d2010051103.pdf|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> In January 2010, Tiruchirappalli became the first city in India where open defecation was prevented in all its slums.<ref name="gramalaya">{{cite web|title=The first city in India where open defecation prevented in all slums|url=http://www.gramalaya.in/first_ODF_slum.php|date=January 15, 2010|publisher=Gramalaya|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref>

Tiruchirappalli comes under the Tiruchi Telecom District of the [[Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited]] (BSNL), India's state-owned telecom and internet services provider.<ref name="thehindu_20100412">{{cite news|title=Tiruchi BSNL wins award|url=http://hindu.com/2010/04/12/stories/2010041257640200.htm|work=The Hindu|date=April 12, 2010|accessdate=2011-05-20}}</ref>There are a total of about 20,000 business telephone subscribers in the city.<ref name="thehindu_20110518">{{cite news|title=Commercial telephone directory released|work=The Hindu|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/05/18/stories/2011051863040300.htm|date=May 18, 2011|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref>Both global system for mobile communications (GSM) and Code division multiple (CDMA) mobile services are available.<ref name="thehindu_20080903">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/09/03/stories/2008090359700500.htm |title=Tamil Nadu / Tiruchi News : In-plant training offered |work=The Hindu |date=March 9, 2008|accessdate = 2011-05-11}}</ref>  Apart from telecom, BSNL also provides [[broadband internet]] service.<ref name="bsnlbroadbandlist">{{cite web|title=List of cities where BSNL broadband service is available (As on 01.01.2007)|url=http://www.bsnl.co.in/service/broadband_list_of_cities.pdf|accessdate=2011-05-20|publisher=Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited (BSNL)}}</ref>
BSNL began offering wireless internet services with the commencement of [[Evolution-Data Optimized]] (EVDO) transmission in 2008.<ref name="thehindu_20080903" /> Tiruchirappalli is one of the few cities in India where BSNL's Caller Line Identification (CLI) based internet service Netone is available.<ref name="bsnl_netone">{{cite web|title=LIST of cities where Calling Line Identification (CLI) Based Internet Service is available|url=http://www.bsnl.co.in/service/cities_cli.htm|publisher=Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited|accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref> Softnet (STPI), Tata VSNL, Bharti and Reliance are other major boradband internet service providers in the city.<ref name="elcot_cityprofile">{{cite web|title=Destination: Trichy|url=http://www.elcot.in/tiruchy.php|publisher=Electronics Corporation of India|accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref>

Tiruchirappalli has a [[Passport office|passport office]] which started to function from March 23, 1983. Apart from Tiruchirappalli, it also caters to the needs of seven adjacent districts namely, Karur, Nagappattinam, Perambalur, Pudukkottai, Thanjavur, Ariyalur and Thiruvarur.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regional passport office|url=http://passport.gov.in/trichy.html|publisher=Trichy passport office|accessdate=2011-05-21}}</ref>


